The dissociation energy ($D_0$) is the energy required to dissociate a molecule into its constituent atoms. For $\mathrm{H}_2$, $D_0 = 4.478 \, \mathrm{eV}$, and for $\mathrm{H}_2^{+}$, $D_0 = 2.651 \, \mathrm{eV}$. The ionization energy of $\mathrm{H}_2$ can be related to these values through a thermodynamic cycle.

