Problem: 5.3-15. Three drugs are being tested for use as the treatment of a certain disease. Let $p_1, p_2$, and $p_3$ represent the probabilities of success for the respective drugs. As three patients come in, each is given one of the drugs in a random order. After $n=10$ "triples" and assuming independence, compute the probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the drugs exceeds eight if, in fact, $p_1=p_2=p_3=0.7$
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: ## Step 1
The problem involves calculating the probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the drugs exceeds eight when three drugs are tested on three patients in a random order, with $n=10$ "triples". The probability of success for each drug is given as $p_1 = p_2 = p_3 = 0.7$.

## Step 2
To solve this, we first need to understand that the number of successes for each drug follows a binomial distribution since we have a fixed number of trials ($n=10$), each trial has only two possible outcomes (success or failure), the probability of success is the same for every trial ($p = 0.7$), and the trials are independent.

## Step 3
For each drug, the probability of getting exactly $k$ successes out of $n=10$ trials is given by the binomial probability formula $P(X = k) = \binom{n}{k} p^k (1-p)^{n-k}$, where $\binom{n}{k}$ is the binomial coefficient.

## Step 4
We are interested in the probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the drugs exceeds eight. This means we need to calculate $P(X > 8)$ for one drug and then consider the scenario for all three drugs.

## Step 5
$P(X > 8) = P(X = 9) + P(X = 10)$. Using the binomial probability formula, we calculate $P(X = 9)$ and $P(X = 10)$ for one drug.

## Step 6
$P(X = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (1-0.7)^{10-9} = 10 \times (0.7)^9 \times (0.3)^1 = 10 \times 0.040353607 \times 0.3 = 0.121060821$.

## Step 7
$P(X = 10) = \binom{10}{10} (0.7)^{10} (1-0.7)^{10-10} = 1 \times (0.7)^{10} \times (0.3)^0 = 1 \times 0.02824752 \times 1 = 0.02824752$.

## Step 8
Thus, $P(X > 8) = 0.121060821 + 0.02824752 = 0.149308341$.

## Step 9
The probability that at least one of the three drugs has more than 8 successes is $1 - P(\text{all three have 8 or fewer successes}) = 1 - (P(X \leq 8))^3 = 1 - (1 - P(X > 8))^3$.


## Step 10
$P(X > 8) = 0.149308341$, so $1 - P(X > 8) = 1 - 0.149308341 = 0.850691659$.


## Step 11
$(1 - P(X > 8))^3 = (0.850691659)^3 = 0.615825235$.


## Step 12
Therefore, the probability that at least one drug exceeds eight successes is $1 - 0.615825235 = 0.384174765$.


## Step 13
Rounding this to a reasonable number of significant figures gives us approximately $0.384$.

The final answer is $[0.384]$.
